00:49:25.130 --> 00:49:27.130
I don't know to that,
actually, because I've not

00:49:27.130 --> 00:49:29.690
kept up with that
interstellar stuff very well.

00:49:29.690 --> 00:49:32.150
But I know that it's
basically allowing us

00:49:32.150 --> 00:49:34.510
to look into our local galaxy.

00:49:34.510 --> 00:49:37.667
And I don't exactly know
when that dust was formed.

00:49:37.667 --> 00:49:39.500
But what they've been
able to do is actually

00:49:39.500 --> 00:49:42.470
measure the isotopes of the
elements of that material,

00:49:42.470 --> 00:49:44.420
and that allows us
to understand a lot

00:49:44.420 --> 00:49:46.430
about our local
environment, like what

00:49:46.430 --> 00:49:48.420
our solar system formed from.

00:49:48.420 --> 00:49:50.570
And obviously we expect
that different galaxies

00:49:50.570 --> 00:49:53.420
are going to be different
compositions, because they

00:49:53.420 --> 00:49:55.034
formed at different times maybe.

00:49:55.034 --> 00:49:57.200
I mean, we still don't
really understand all of that

00:49:57.200 --> 00:49:59.797
because we haven't been
able to sample it or look

00:49:59.797 --> 00:50:02.130
at it very clearly because
these things are so far away.

00:50:02.130 --> 00:50:05.330
So it's kind of understanding
a little bit further back

00:50:05.330 --> 00:50:07.340
in our history what is in there.

00:50:07.340 --> 00:50:11.120
But yeah, I'd have
to say I'm not sure.

00:50:11.120 --> 00:50:13.010
AUDIENCE: So recently
there was big news

